      "content": "The persistent racial inequality in the United States is not a matter of individual failings, but a direct, quantifiable outcome of centuries of racially biased policy and economic exploitation. Systemic racism has intentionally engineered disparities, creating a wealth chasm where the descendants of marginalized groups are structurally disadvantaged from birth. Therefore, wealth redistribution is not a radical proposal, but the only logical mechanism to dismantle the economic scaffolding of white supremacy.\n\nThe first critical pillar of this argument is the undeniable link between historical policy and present-day poverty. Policies like redlining, discriminatory lending practices, and unequal educational funding systematically denied Black and Brown families the opportunity to build generational wealth. These actions were not accidents; they were deliberate tools of oppression that starved communities of capital. Consequently, the current wealth gap is not a natural market outcome, but a direct inheritance of state-sanctioned theft and exclusion.",
